Functionally speaking, what need to be initialised for this lab.
ANS:

Baud Rate for communiction btw MCU and PC agreed apon.

For Asynchronous transmition:
The UBRR0(Usart Baud Rate Register)  register needs to be populated with:
------------------------------------------------------------------------
float ubrr0 = ( (F_CPU / (16.0 * baud_rate)) - 1); when U2X0=0.
OR
float ubrr0 = ( (F_CPU / (8.0 * baud_rate)) - 1); when U2X0=1

UBRR0 set to an integer:
-----------------------
UBRR0A to be setup:

UBRR0A = UBRR0 cast to an int.

If UBRR0A  is set  with a  rounded up/down number  to get  the closest
integer.

Then UBRR0 = UBRR0A, UBRR0 is set to an int.



BitSettings():
-----------

USART CSR0B(Control and Status Register B).
------------------------------------------
Set bit TXEN0(TX/Transmitter Enable)
Set bit RXEN0(RX/Reciver Enable)


UCSR0C bits need to be set.  It controls data bits, parity, stop bits:
---------------------------------------------------------------------

UCSR0C |= 3 << UCSZ00 sets UCSZ00 amd UCSZ01.
Thus UCSR0C becomes => 8bit data transmission:
UCSZ02		UCSZ01 UCSZ00
0(in USR0B)	1	1

This leaves the rest of UCSR0C in default mode:
UMSEL01=0 UMSEL00=0 => Asynchronous USART.
UPM01=0 UPM00=0 => Parity Mode Disabled
USBS0=0 => 1 Stop Bit.


USE Claude Haiku 4.5 version of this fn as it makes settings more clear:
Fosc, internal Crystal Arduino r3 = 16MHz
ubrr0 = (Fosc/prescale factor * baud rate) - 1
U2Xn=0, prescale factor is 2/4/2=16
U2Xn=1, prescale factor is 2/4=8



When sending a string from MCU to PC, how to know when to stop sending.

ANS:  When the null terminator character ie '\0' is reached.



When reading a string from PC in MCU, how to know when to stop reciving.

ANS:
Then  you have  to check  wether you  got an  '\r'(carrige return)  or
'\n'(newline character/line  feed) Make sure that  your serial monitor
is set up for sending a CRLF.

You must  make sure the RXC0  bit is set in  the UCSR0A(Control Status
Register A) to indicate there is unread data in the receive buffer, it
is cleared when the receive buffer is empty.



How numbers are transmitted from PC to MCU?

ANS: They are sent as ASCII text.   One character at a time, eg '1' ==
0x31 in ASCII.  In the MCU  atmega328p stores the recived byte in UDR0
I/O  register.  When  the RXC0  is  set there  is unread  data in  the
receive buffer.  UDR0(USART Data Register) is ready for reading.  Then
you  use a  function like  atoi()/atof() to  convert the  ASCII to  an
integer/float value.  Then RXC0 is cleared when the buffer is empty.




How numbers are transmitted from MCU to PC?

ANS: usart_send_num() sends data from the MCU to the PC.  It writes to
the transmit  register, USART TX/RX IO  register, register UDRE0(Usart
Data Register  Empty) flag is  set in the  UCSR0A.  TXEN0 needs  to be
set.

dtostrf(num,  width, precision,  string)  converts float  to an  ASCII
string.  We add a  string terminator '\0' so the PC  knows when we are
at the end of a string).

Then send the null terminated string to the PC.
